{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-template-tsx","path":"/blog/collatz-conjecture-multiply","result":{"pageContext":{"slug":"/blog/collatz-conjecture-multiply","markdownRemark":{"htmlAst":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"I stumbled across an "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00224-020-09986-5"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"interesting paper"}]},{"type":"text","value":", which shows that you can multiply two numbers by using the Collatz conjecture (and assuming it to be true for the numbers you are dealing with)."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This post contains my summary and understanding of how this method works."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h1","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Background"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h2","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Collatz conjecture"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h3","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Definition"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collatz_conjecture"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Collatz conjecture"}]},{"type":"text","value":", also known as the $3n + 1$ problem, is a simple to describe, yet unsolved, problem in discrete mathematics. The conjecture states that if you start with a positive integer $n$ and apply the following rule to it:"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"ul","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If the number ($n$) is even, divide it by two: $\\frac{n}{2}$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If the number ($n$) is odd, multiply it by 3 and add one: $3n + 1$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The number will eventually land in the cycle $4 \\rightarrow 2 \\rightarrow 1 \\rightarrow 4$. The conjecture states: this the only cycle. There is no proof to confirm this, however, we have tested up to a very large number and the conjecture seems to hold. Thus, for all practical purposes: the conjecture is true."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The rule can be mathematically written as:"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"f(n) =\n\\begin{cases}\n\\frac{n}{2} &\\text{if } n \\equiv 0 \\text{ (mod 2)} \\\n3n + 1 &\\text{otherwise}\n\\end{cases}"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h3","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Examples"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$10$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"ul","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$5$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$16$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$8$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$4$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$2$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$1$ (cycle starts)"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$18$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"ul","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$9$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$28$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$14$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$7$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$22$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$11$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$34$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$17$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$52$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$26$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$13$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$40$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$20$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$10$ (use above)"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h1","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Method"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h2","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Definitions"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h3","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Collatz Function"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Define the Collatz function, $F$, as the Collatz conjecture with path of dividing by 2 compressed into one step, that is:"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Given $$x$$, a positive odd integer:"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$$\nF(x) = \\frac{3x + 1}{2^{\\text{ctz}(3x + 1)}}\n$$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"ul","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$$\\text{ctz}(x)$$ gives the number of factors of 2 in a number, i.e. count the\ntrailing zeros of a number in binary"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h3","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Collatz sequence and $k$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"ul","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The Collatz sequence, is the sequence of numbers produced by the Collatz\nfunction until it reaches the number $1$ for the first time"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Define $k$ as the number of steps until the Collatz series lands on $1$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In other words, the Collatz sequence can be shown mathematically like so:\n$$\nx, F_1(x), F_2(x), ..., F_{k-1}(x), 1\n$$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h2","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"How to Divide: $$\\frac{m}{a}$$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Let's multiply the Collatz function series by $$a$$, we get:"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$$\nax, aF_1(x), aF_2(x), ..., aF_{k-1}(x), a\n$$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Let $$m = ax$$, we get"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"$$\n\\begin{aligned}\na F(x) & = a \\frac{3x + 1}{2^{\\text{ctz}{(a(3x + 1))}}} \\\n& = \\frac{3ax + a}{2^{\\text{ctz}{(3ax + a)}}} \\\n& = \\frac{3m + a}{2^{\\text{ctz}{(3m + a)}}} \\\n& = G(m)\n\\end{aligned}\n$$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"NOTES: $$ctz(3m+a) = ctz(3m+1)$$ when $$a$$ is odd"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Assuming $a \\mid m$ ($a$ divides $m$), we can:"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"ol","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Start with $m$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Use $G(m)$ until we get to $a$\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"ul","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Record what we've done to get there"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"i.e. save the result of $\\text{ctz}(3x + 1)$ along the way and $k$\n(the number of steps)"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Backtrack using the same form of operations (in reverse) with $F(x)$ whilst\nstarting at $1$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"i.e. we have a division algorithm using the Collatz conjecture"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h2","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"How to Multiply: $ax$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Now, how do we multiply? Simple:"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"ul","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Start with $x$ and use $F(x)$ until we get to $$1$$\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"ul","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Record what we've done (save the $k$ steps)"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Now, start with $$a$$ and backtrack with $G(x)$ (with the saved $k$ steps),\nwhich will get us to $ax$"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}]}],"data":{"quirksMode":false}},"frontmatter":{"date":"August 06, 2022","title":"How to Multiply with the 3n + 1 series (Collatz Conjecture)","state":"publish","slug":"/blog/collatz-conjecture-multiply","tags":"math","source":null,"code":null},"fields":{"slug":"/content/collatz_conjecture_multiply"}}}},"staticQueryHashes":["2744905544"]}